1. Introduction¶

The landscape of combat sports has undergone a remarkable transformation in recent years, with Mixed Martial Arts (MMA) and the Ultimate Fighting Championship (UFC) at the forefront of this change. Once considered fringe sports, MMA and UFC have surged in popularity, captivating audiences worldwide.

As the popularity of MMA has grown, more and more people have tried to predict the outcome of fights not only to purely compare the skills of fighters but also as a way to earn money through sports betting. In this project we attempt to gain insights into one of the largest MMA databases publicly availaible and try to draw inferences from our data to all of MMA to answer these questions.

2. Data Curation¶

In this project we use this MMA dataset from Kaggle which was first compiled in May of 2023.

Why did we chose this dataset?¶

We chose this dataset because it was the largest MMA database we could find and it also had a plethora of detailed stats as well as differential stats which we thought would be very useful for our goals.

Data Cleaning¶

We use some simple python tools to clean our dataset and prepare it for our future analysis. We start off by dropping all data points which are duplicates or are missing values. We also noticed that the 'age' column in the dataset contained the age of fighters when the dataset was created which was completely irrelevant to the fight due to which we removed it.

In [6]:
df_drop = df.dropna().drop_duplicates()
df_drop = df_drop.drop(columns = ["age"])

We also introduced a new integer column, 'Age', to measure the age of fighters in years at the time of the fight, which is more pertinent to the fight's outcome. Additionally, we've converted the 'date' and 'dob' columns from strings to datetime formats.

In [7]:
df_drop["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df_drop["date"])
df_drop["dob"] = pd.to_datetime(df_drop["dob"])
df_drop["Age"] = (df_drop["date"] - df_drop["dob"])
df_drop["Age"] =  df_drop["Age"].apply(lambda x : int(str(x // 365)[0:2]))

Data Formatting¶

While we have "df", our original dataframe and "df_drop", the dataframe which has undergone cleaning, we want two datasets one of which contains only the stats of a fight before the fight starts and the other which contains both pre and post fight stats.

Scientific Method - Hypothesis Test For Reach Differential (1)¶

We want to test whether reach differential (differential stats are calculated by diving the two individual's technique stats), affects the outcome of the match.

Null Hypothesis: Reach differential has no impact on the outcome of the match.

Alternative Hypothesis: Reach differential has an effect on the outcome of the match.

We use a two sample t-test to test for a correlation.

We will use an significance level of 0.5

In [30]:
df_w = df_drop[df_drop['result'] == 1]
df_l = df_drop[df_drop['result'] == 0]

bins = np.linspace(df_drop["reach_differential"].min(), df_drop["reach_differential"].max(), 20)

hist_w, _ = np.histogram(df_w["reach_differential"], bins=bins)
hist_l, _ = np.histogram(df_l["reach_differential"], bins=bins)

total_count = hist_w + hist_l

percent_winners = (hist_w / total_count) * 100
percent_losers = (hist_l / total_count) * 100

plt.bar(bins[:-1], percent_winners, width=np.diff(bins), alpha=0.5, label='Winners')
plt.bar(bins[:-1], percent_losers, width=np.diff(bins), alpha=0.5, label='Losers', bottom=percent_winners)

plt.xlabel('Reach Differential')
plt.ylabel('Percentage')
plt.title('Percentage of Winners vs. Losers for Reach Differential')
plt.legend()

plt.show()

Since this p value falls well below our significance value, we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that our result is statistically significant. The mixed histogram plot above also supports our test result. We can clearly see that a higher reach differential has a positive impact on a fighters chances of winning a given match.

Scientific Method : Hypothesis Testing (Chi-Squared) For Name (2)¶

We want to see if which features are important in predicting result since that is our final goal

We first test a feature that we think think may have an affect which is the name of fighter and its correlation to result

Null Hypothesis: Name of the fighter has no effect on results

Alternatve Hypothesis: Name of the fighter has an effect on the results

We use chi squared to determine correlation

We set signifcance level to 0.05

Scientific Method: Hypothesis Testing (Anova) For Age Range (3)¶

We want to identify the features which are important for figuring out how to get the results. We hypothesize that age range might be one of these features. To this end, we compare age range and results with ANOVA, to determine if there is any correlation

Null Hypothesis: There is no correlation between age range and result

Alternative Hypothesis: There is correlation between age range and result

Level of significance: We set our alpha value at .05

In [44]:
def age_r(x):
    if x > 45:
        return "45-50"
    elif x > 40:
        return "40-45"
    elif x > 35:
        return "35-40"
    elif x > 30:
        return "30-35"
    elif x > 25:
        return "25-30"
    else:
        return "20-25"

df_drop["age_range"] = df_drop["Age"].apply(age_r)

        thtf.append(row["result"])
    elif row["age_range"] == '35-40':
        tfft.append(row["result"])
    elif row["age_range"] == '40-45':
        ftfv.append(row["result"])
    else:
        fvff.append(row["result"])

Based on the analysis conducted, it is evident that the alternate hypothesis can be supported due to the low p-value obtained from the statistical tests. The results indicate that there is sufficient evidence to conclude that there is a significant relationship or effect as hypothesized. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis.

Overall Conclusion for Data exploration¶

We can firstly conclude that reach differential is an important feature for determing result based on our statistical test giving a p value < level of significance. Secondly we can also conclude who the fighter is an important characteristic in our dataset that affects the result of the match based on our statistical test using chi-squared. Thirdly, we can conclude that age range does have significant affect and correlation to the result of the match. Having examined the dataset through these scientific methods we can conclude that our analysis to be used will most likely be k nearest neighbours or random forest.

5. Visualization¶

From our feature importance we know that age differential matters to the result of determing who wins and loses. In this visualization we graph average significant strike attempts against the age. We again the scale the distribution curve logarithmically to better show the correlation. Notice that the curve shows attempts are less when fighter are younger and older. We can correlate this with age differential as when the fighter is older or younger their will most likely be a higher age differential when it comes to fighting the other opponent. Because the fighter is older or younger, they are less likely to win, which also explains the less number of attempts to do significant strikes.

In [323]:
age_groups = df_filtered.groupby('Age')['sig_strikes_accuracy_differential'].mean().reset_index()
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.title('Histogram of Average Significant Strikes Attempts Differential by Age')
plt.yscale('log')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Here we are plotting the average age differential vs. the recent average significant strikes landed. This is basically the average age differential and strikes landed for the past fights the fighter has participated in. We also color the points by their actual age. What we see that is that older fighter are typically having a higher age differntial with their opponent meaning they are more often then not fighting younger opponents. Also notice the bell curve like shape formed by the points. When the age differential is closer to 1 and the ages are around 27-33, there are higher significant striked being landed by the fighter. With higher strikes landed, the more likely the fighter is to win a fight. This connects to our insight from the primary analysis that age differential does play a big factor to determing the wins and losses.

6. Insights And Conclusion¶

Overall, the conclusions from our finding is that it is difficult to predict the results of a match, based on just the pre-fight data, as our overall accuracy was .56 with the Random Forest model, which is considered to be one of the best models with regard to classification. The features that we found were best for the prediction was the age differential between the fighter and the opponent, or how different the ages of a fighter and his opponent was. We found that this also correlated with how many strikes a fighter landed during their fight, helping us figure out why age differential was so important in determining the outcome of a match.
